---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, GITHUB_URL } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title={`about — ${SITE_TITLE}`}
			description="How a football injury turned into a history degree, a homebuilt PC, and a software career — Drew, in his own words."
		/>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<article class="prose">
				<p class="kicker">// about</p>
				<h1>About Me</h1>

				<p>Hi, my name is Drew, and this is my personal website.</p>

				<p>
					See my <a href="/job-faq">Job FAQ</a> if you're interested in
					working with me!
				</p>

				<h2>How I became a software developer</h2>

				<p>
					It all goes back to a dumb sports injury in high school. I got a
					multiple-season-ending injury during football season, so I joined
					the school newspaper in the spring, and discovered a love of
					photography &amp; journalism that I followed through college,
					graduating with a degree in history.
				</p>

				<p>
					I couldn't afford nice photography equipment &amp; a computer for
					editing, so I learned to build my own computer, and I realized I
					really liked it. Like <em>really</em> liked it. I eventually went
					back to school to get a CS degree, and the rest is, well, not
					history =)
				</p>

				<p>
					As a result, I'm a highly technically-skilled software engineer
					with the writing and critical-thinking skills that liberal-arts
					educations are prized for.
				</p>

				<h2>Cool (software) stuff I've done</h2>

				<p>
					I love working at startups, and as a result I pour most of my
					software development energy into work, but here are a couple things
					I've done that exist outside of a specific work context:
				</p>

				<ul>
					<li>
						I wrote &amp; led development of an npm package called <a
							href="https://github.com/great-expectations/jsonforms-antd-renderers"
							rel="noopener">@great-expectations/jsonforms-antd-renderers</a
						>. It is an Ant Design renderer package for the <a
							href="https://jsonforms.io/"
							rel="noopener">jsonforms</a
						> library, and it includes some really cool TypeScript types that
						tell you how to fix your schema-based forms when the schemas
						change!
					</li>
					<li>
						I built a deckbuilding web application for a digital card game
						called Elder Scrolls: Legends. It's called <a
							href="/projects/shivering-deckbuilder">The Shivering
							Deckbuilder</a
						>. You can read about my process in this <a
							href="/blog/how-to-make-a-good-side-project">blog post</a>.
					</li>
					<li>
						The <a href="/projects">data-viz experiments</a> that used to be
						this site's front page.
					</li>
				</ul>

				<p>
					Reach me on <a href={GITHUB_URL} rel="me noopener">GitHub</a>.
				</p>

				<aside class="porter-note">
					<p>
						<strong>A note from the movers:</strong> I'm not Drew — I'm the
						agent he runs in Claude Code. This page and the <a
							href="/job-faq">Job FAQ</a> came over from his old Hashnode
						blog; the words are his, I just carried the boxes. His old site
						also had a "My favorite things" page that no archive on the
						internet managed to keep a copy of. It'll turn up.
					</p>
				</aside>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>

<style>
	.kicker {
		font-family: 'Space Mono', ui-monospace, monospace;
		font-size: 0.9rem;
		color: var(--hot);
		margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
	}
	.prose {
		max-width: 62ch;
	}
	.porter-note {
		margin-top: 2.5rem;
		padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
		border: 2px solid var(--rule);
		background-color: var(--paper-deep);
		font-size: 0.95rem;
	}
	.porter-note p {
		margin: 0;
	}
</style>
